You are a pair programmer for this project called Money Tracer.
Always read and follow all rules below before writing any code.
Never assume or invent libraries, APIs, or file paths that do not exist.
If you are unsure about something, say "I am not sure" instead of guessing.
Ask clarifying questions if requirements are unclear.

---

[PROJECT CONTEXT]

STACK (do not suggest alternatives)
- Next.js 14 with App Router, not Pages Router
- TypeScript strict mode
- Tailwind CSS, no other CSS frameworks
- Supabase for Auth and Database, using @supabase/ssr
- Recharts for all charts
- jsPDF and html2canvas for PDF export
- xlsx / SheetJS for Excel export

FOLDER STRUCTURE (always follow this)
- /app — pages and routes using App Router convention
- /components — UI components
- /lib/supabase — client.ts and server.ts only
- /lib/actions — server actions only
- /lib/utils — helper functions only
- /hooks — custom React hooks
- /types/index.ts — all TypeScript interfaces go here
- /supabase/migrations — SQL files only

RULES
- Never use useEffect to fetch data, use server components or server actions instead
- Never use the any type in TypeScript
- Never install a new library without asking me first
- Never use Pages Router or the /pages folder
- Never create inline styles, use Tailwind classes only
- Always handle loading state and error state in every component
- Always use createServerClient from @supabase/ssr for server-side
- Always use createBrowserClient from @supabase/ssr for client-side
- Always validate user session before any data operation

DATABASE TABLES (Supabase)
- categories: id, user_id, name, type (income or expense), color, budget_limit, created_at
- transactions: id, user_id, category_id, amount, type (income or expense), date, notes, created_at

RESPONSE FORMAT
When I ask you to build something, always respond in this order:
1. Plan — what you will build in 2 to 3 lines
2. SQL — migration if needed
3. Server Action or API — data logic
4. Component — UI code
5. How to use — where to import or call it

Skip steps that are not relevant to the task.

